comment: From my experience of working with homeless people it is always good to contact any Association in your area that works for them. Some homeless people are not able to understand  what you are providing to them cos they might have deficiency disorder, like many I have met in Usa. Other have been rejected by the society and can def understand their status and be more willing to take your helps, medication and whatever your provide. Many others are most of the time on drugs and are addicted to it so can be hard for them to even communicate. It is a noble act to support their journey ❤️expecaully on a winter time, but the best things is to always calls someone in your area who are skilled enough to give a shelter. ❤️❤️Thanks for inspiring many of us with your post and noble gesture

comment: We love @shelterkc 🩵
Every single one of these @wearetrellis people ROCK
thank you for sharing this important information <3

I was in the Horton St. Goodwill this past Thursday.  I witnessed a man who was struggling to fit himself into a pop up style child’s play tent.  It barely came to his waist and did not fit his head or both arms.  I heard him muttering that “ this might work”. I believe he was hoping to buy himself some shelter from the elements.  The scene was heartbreaking.  Had it been something that might have actually worked, I would have offered to purchase it for him.  Unfortunately, the store did not have anything of use for shelter.  It seems London City Council doesn’t either!  It bothers my conscience that other Londoners are sleeping in the heat, the rain, the cold, the snow and not feeling safe or likely not sleeping either…who could?  Fortunately, I have no experience with addiction but it wouldn’t surprise me if many of these folks “ self medicate” to help deal with their miserable lives.  How is it that the “ successful “ people who form London City Council are having such a time consuming struggle to figure out an overdue solution to London’s homeless crisis?  Did the City of London not receive a VERY generous donation especially earmark d to solve this issue?

Last week when we were in Canmore a young man was standing outside of the A&W. He was cold, hungry and looking for a ride to Calgary. He walked in while we were eating and then back out again. My son looked at him and said that’s pretty sad. I responded with saying yes it is, should be get him something to eat. It was really special to bring him up to the till, ask him what he wanted and then wish him all the best in the new year. ❤️I don’t care what his story is, I just cared that he was fed and felt the connection from one human to another. I hope my son will always remember that lesson. I also hope he sat down to eat his meal and felt he belonged there too.
